\left|\infty-k\right|=-k, \forall k\in \mathbb{N}
k
C_k^\infty = {\infty\choose k}
\left|\infty\right|
(1+x)
\ln{(1+x)}
{\infty\choose 0}\equiv 1
 {\infty\choose k} = \frac{\left|\infty\right|\left|\infty-1\right|\left|\infty-2\right|\dots\left|\infty-(k-1)\right|}{k!} = \frac{\left|\infty\right|(-1)(-2)\dots(-(k-1))}{k!} = \left|\infty\right|\frac{(-1)^{(k-1)}}{k} 
 (1+x)^\infty = \sum_{k=0}^\infty {\infty\choose k}x^k = {\infty\choose 0} + \left|\infty\right|\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{(k-1)}}{k}x^k 
 (1+x)^\infty = \left|\infty\right|\ln{(1+x)} + 1 
 \ln{x} = \frac{x^\infty-1}{\left|\infty\right|} 
 \lim_{y\to 0}{\frac{x^y-1}{y}} = \ln{x} 
